<br>
Teachers are role models and children are naive. I do not want a selfish teacher as my child’s role model. Some teachers just go to 'work' to get a paycheck and others 'teach' because that is what they love. As a parent of a 3rd grader and 1st grader, and a mom whose dream is to become a teacher, I can certainly tell the difference between each teachers attitude from year to year. <br>
<br>
If my children are going to spend 7 hours a day, 5 days a week in a classroom for 13 years, you better believe that those teachers are instilling morals and values into my child, whether I want them to or not. For anyone to put <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> all</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of the blame on the parents for things that children do is absolutely ignorant. If it takes a community to raise a child, it takes a community to ruin a child.<br>
<br>
The blame you can put on the parent is the act of being oblivious to their children’s surroundings. The parent who does nothing when their son or daughter acts out in a violent nature or the parent who does not take the time to get to know their children’s friends. The parents who don't monitor the TV programs their kids watch or the parents who don't move their children away from the foul mouthed idiot at the park. <br>
<br>
My responsibility to my family is to make sure that we are not surrounded by useless members of society and when they are, to explain to them why that behavior is unexceptable. I should be able to trust that the school has hired a qualified individual to be a role model and care for my children when I am not there. It's a shame to feel like I need to sit in the classroom and baby-sit the teacher because of the low standards the public school system has for their teaching staff.<br>
<br>
